## âŒ Error: Failed to lookup view "home" in views directory

### ğŸ§  Root Cause:
When you write:
```js
app.set('views', path.resolve("./views"));
```

This line resolves the `views` folder **relative to your current terminal working directory**, not the location of your `index.js` file.

---

### ğŸ’¥ What Happened:

1. You ran this from:
   ```powershell
   PS C:\Users\madan\STACK\NodeJs>
   node "c:\Users\madan\STACK\NodeJs\5URLshort\index.js"
   ```

2. So, `path.resolve("./views")` became:
   ```
   C:\Users\madan\STACK\NodeJs\views
   ```
   âŒ This is wrong, because your actual views folder is:
   ```
   C:\Users\madan\STACK\NodeJs\5URLshort\views
   ```

---

### âœ… When It Worked:

You later ran:
```powershell
PS C:\Users\madan\STACK\NodeJs\5urlshort>
node index.js
```

So `path.resolve("./views")` correctly became:
```
C:\Users\madan\STACK\NodeJs\5URLshort\views
```

âœ… This worked because your terminal path matched your `index.js` location.

---

### ğŸ› ï¸ Permanent Fix (Safe Everywhere):

Use this line instead:
```js
app.set('views', path.join(__dirname, 'views'));
```

âœ… This always resolves the `views` folder **relative to the file location**, regardless of where you run `node` from.

---

### ğŸ“Œ Summary:

| What You Used | Behavior |
|---------------|----------|
| `path.resolve("./views")` | Depends on terminal path (fragile âŒ) |
| `path.join(__dirname, "views")` | Always correct based on file location (safe âœ…) |









## ğŸ§¨ Error: `urls is not defined` in EJS

### âŒ Problem:

When rendering the EJS view, Node.js threw this error:
```
ReferenceError: urls is not defined
    at home.ejs:10
```

### ğŸ“ Cause:

In EJS templates, variables like `urls` are only available if you **explicitly pass them** from the route using `res.render()`.

If you write:
```js
res.render('home'); // âŒ No data passed
```

Then inside `home.ejs`, this will fail:
```ejs
<% urls.forEach(...) %> // âŒ "urls is not defined"
```

Because `urls` does not exist in the template's scope.

---

### âœ… Solution:

Pass the variable to the EJS view like this:
```js
res.render('home', { urls: allUrls });
```

Now, inside your `home.ejs`, you can safely access `urls`:
```ejs
<% urls.forEach(url => { %>
  <li><%= url.shortId %> - <%= url.redirectURL %> - <%= url.visitHistory.length %></li>
<% }) %>
```

---

### âœ… Correct Route Example:

```js
app.get("/test", async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const allUrls = await URL.find({});
    res.render('home', { urls: allUrls }); // âœ… Pass data
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('Error fetching URLs:', err);
    res.status(500).send("Internal Server Error");
  }
});
```

---

### âœ… Correct `home.ejs` View:

```ejs
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Home Page</title>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Welcome to Server</h1>
  <ul>
    <% urls.forEach(url => { %>
      <li><%= url.shortId %> - <%= url.redirectURL %> - <%= url.visitHistory.length %></li>
    <% }) %>
  </ul>
</body>
</html>
```

---

### ğŸ“Œ Summary

| Mistake                          | Fix                                     |
|----------------------------------|------------------------------------------|
| Not passing `urls` to view       | Use `res.render('home', { urls })`       |
| Using `${}` instead of EJS tags  | Use `<%= %>` and `<% %>` in `.ejs` files |
| Running `.ejs` file with `node`  | âŒ Invalid â€” only use Express to render   |
